\begin_layout Subsection
What is Genomic Selection?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Genomic Selection or Genomic Prediction is a new tool that can 
\color blue
predict
\color inherit
 a plant/animal 
\color blue
genetic merit
\color inherit
 based on 
\color blue
scoring DNA
\color inherit
 markers such as single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNP).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename img/genomic-selection-DNA.png
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
GS can predict how an animal’s progeny will perform
\color inherit
 before the traits are measured or even right after the birth without needing
 any other information (such as pedigree).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Genomic Selection (GS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "c"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 1
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing other 0.5

\size scriptsize
GS is based on the principle that information from 
\color blue
a large number of markers, without knowledge of where genes are located,
\color inherit
 can be used to estimate breeding values 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Itemize

\size scriptsize
It is similar to conventional MAS in that genetic information is being used,
 but rather than introducing a single trait (as in MAS), markers can be
 selected that are in common with the training population showing multiple
 favorable traits.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\size scriptsize
In GS, EBVs (also called gEBVs) are calculated from the cumulative effect
 of large numbers of genetic markers covering the whole genome, and these
 values are used to score new potential breeding candidates.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "c"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename img/linkage-map-small.pdf
	lyxscale 30
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing other 0.5

\size scriptsize
It is similar to conventional MAS in that genetic information is used, but
 instead of explicitly introducing a single trait (as in MAS), multiple
 favorable traits are implicitly taken and selected from markers common
 to the training population.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

