\begin_layout Plain Layout
The process of GS includes the following steps, also 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Collection and documentation of phenotype and genotype data for each marker
 of interest in the reference sample (or discovery dataset) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Representation of each genotype by a variable, x, that can have 3 values:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
0 (homozygote for one allele), 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
1 (heterozygote), and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2 (homozygote for the second allele) 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Statistical analysis on a reference population to estimate the effect of
 each marker (w) on the phenotype
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Generation of a prediction equation for the gEBV that combines all the marker
 genotypes with their effects on the predictive value of each animal (see
 below) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Application of the prediction equation to a group of animals for which genotypes
 (but not phenotypes) are available.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Breeding values are estimated and the best animals are selected for breeding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

